From 01db0471afd7c0de471e9402f97a5beb6e3b104d Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Gravio <gravio@uni-muenster.de>
Date: Mon, 27 Apr 2026 11:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] numba cache: disable for recursive @njit functions and their
 callers
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Regression from numba_cache_fix.patch: launch crashes with

    LLVM ERROR: Symbol not found:
      .numba.unresolved$_ZN6mufasa18feature_extractors13perimeter_jit7process...

This is a known numba limitation: @njit(cache=True) doesn't reliably
handle recursive functions or @njit functions that call other @njit
functions in the same module. Numba writes a cached artifact
containing an unresolved symbol reference; on the next load it tries
to resolve the symbol from the cache, doesn't find it, LLVM aborts
the process.

Three recursive @njit functions exist in the codebase:
  perimeter_jit.process       (recursive quickhull step)
  feature_extraction_supplement_mixin.peak_ratio
  circular_statistics.circular_range

Plus two functions that call process() from within @njit context in
the same module:
  perimeter_jit.jitted_hull
  perimeter_jit.jitted_centroid

Disable cache=True on all five. The remaining 117 @njit/@jit
functions retain caching and continue to provide the warm-launch
speedup. The five reverted functions JIT-compile every cold start as
before — small constant cost, far less than the breakage.

Verified:
- All five files compile after the revert
- The decorator forms restored exactly match pre-cache state

Future: A more thorough fix would either:
  1. Refactor process to be iterative (eliminates recursion entirely)
  2. Move process to a separate module imported by jitted_hull /
     jitted_centroid (bypasses the same-module cross-reference bug)
Either way is out of scope here — the priority is restoring a working
launch.
